title: For Sale:  USED - Czech CZ 24, Holster, 2 Mags, Very Early Pistol (ICN8182)
postcontent: Very early 1926 production CZ Model 1924 (vz. 24), in .380 ACP, that was the standard Czechoslovak Army pistol of the inter-war period manufactured by Česka Zbrojovka (CZ) in Prague (as displayed on a rib on the top of the slide “Česka Zbrojovka A.S. v Praze”). Serial Number: 22059. No import marks. All components match: barrel, frame, and slide. It was an improved version of the CZ 22, which had been licensed from Mauser. Production of the CZ 24 started in August 1925. The original order for 20,000 pistols was completed in June 1926. More orders followed, and by the end of 1929, 100,000 pistols had been accepted by the Military and Gendarmerie, called in Czechoslovakia the “Četnictvo”. Overall, approximately 200,000 CZ 24 pistols were made. An inventory on January 1, 1939, showed the Czechoslovak Army and Air Force had on hand 171,756 CZ 24 pistols. The regular serial number range for the CZ 24 pistol is: 12,000-190,000 (there were some pistols produced as part of small international orders/contracts in a separate serial number range, for example, all 9-shot CZ 24 pistols range from serial number 1 to about 3,100, and are dated from 1929 to 1931). The serial number of this pistol is 22,059. It was a part of the original order for 20,000 CZ 24 pistols completed in June 1926. The pistol is factory dated 26 (1926) and it stayed in the factory warehouse until purchased by the Military also in 1926. It displays the 1926 acceptance “J, rampant lion, 26” mark of Czechoslovak Military. The pistol is unit marked to the Czechoslovak Army’s 6th infantry regiment (6P 615). CZ 24 is a meticulously crafted, well-built, robust, and reliable pistol that was very highly thought of at the time. During the German occupation (March 1939 – May 1945), the Czechoslovak Armed Forces were disarmed, and all the weapons were utilized by Germany and its allies. The CZ 24 pistols were not marked by the Germans, in any way, except for those used by the German Navy. CZ 24 pistols were also issued to the German Air Force, and Waffen-SS. The pistol is fitted with one-piece, smooth wood grips. Magazine capacity is eight rounds, and a Mauser Model 1910-style safety switch is mounted to the left of the pistol. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap holster containing one extra CZ 24 magazine.

title: For Sale:  USED - CZ 24 High Polish Pistol, .380ACP, 1 Mag (ICN8177)
postcontent: Late 1937 production CZ Model 1924 (vz. 24), in .380 ACP, that was the standard Czechoslovak Army pistol of the inter-war period manufactured by Česka Zbrojovka (CZ) in Prague (as displayed on a rib on the top of the slide “Česka Zbrojovka A.S. v Praze”). Serial Number: 125897. No import marks. All components match: barrel, frame, and slide. It has 90% of its original bright blue finish remaining. The trigger, hammer, and extractor retain about 90% of the original straw color. While similar looking, this is not a CZ 27 pistol. CZ 24 was an improved version of the CZ 22, which had been licensed from Mauser. Production of the CZ 24 started in August 1925. The original order for 20,000 pistols was completed in June 1926. Overall, approximately 200,000 CZ 24 pistols were made. An inventory on January 1, 1939, showed the Czechoslovak Army and Air Force had on hand 171,756 CZ 24 pistols. The regular serial number range for the CZ 24 pistol is: 12,000-190,000. The serial number of this pistol is 125,897. The pistol displays the 1937 acceptance “J, rampant lion, 37” mark of Czechoslovak Military. CZ 24 is a meticulously crafted, well-built, robust, and reliable pistol that was very highly thought of at the time. During the German occupation (March 1939 – May 1945), the Czechoslovak Armed Forces were disarmed, and all the weapons were utilized by Germany and its allies. The CZ 24 pistols were not marked by the Germans, in any way, except for those used by the German Navy. CZ 24 pistols were also issued to the German Air Force, and Waffen-SS. Magazine capacity is eight rounds, and a Mauser Model 1910-style safety switch is mounted to the left of the pistol. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is generous). Unlike early CZ 24 pistols fitted with one-piece wood grips, our later (production) CZ 24 is fitted with original one-piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) excellent grips with no cracks or chips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. While CZ 24 pistols are quite common, it is difficult to find one in such exceptional condition. It would make a fine addition to any collection. Comes with a small plastic pistol case.

postcontent: Custom-refinished CZ-83 .380 caliber pistol. Serial Number: 21417. All serial numbers match. This firearm has been completely disassembled “down to the last pin and spring”. Each part has been inspected for excessive wear and tear, and then cleaned in an ultrasonic cleaner to insure a smooth functioning pistol. Most parts were blasted with aluminum oxide to remove the old finish and custom Duracoated for a fine and durable finish. The pistol was then safety and function tested to ensure your satisfaction on the range. Manufactured by the Czechoslovak firm Česká zbrojovka the vz. 83 replaced the 7.62x25mm Tokarev vz. 52 pistol in Czechoslovak military service in 1983. It is a compact, double-action, semi-automatic pistol with a conventional blow back action. This type of action allows the barrel to remain solidly fixed to the frame, resulting in improved accuracy over pistols with pivoting barrels (like the U.S. M1911 series). The low bore axis of the vz. 83 provides for less muzzle rise and quicker follow-up shots. For added convenience, both the frame-mounted thumb safety and the magazine release are ambidextrous. Comes with a black leather holster for the CZ 83, two (2) factory 12-round magazines (with regular and aluminum base pads), and two (2) extra “CZ” wood grips. title: For Sale:  USED - Czech CZ 24, .380ACP,1 Mag, Very Early Production (ICN8175)
postcontent: Early 1927 production CZ Model 1924 (vz. 24), in .380 ACP, that was the standard Czechoslovak Army pistol of the inter-war period manufactured by Česka Zbrojovka (CZ) in Prague (as displayed on a rib on the top of the slide “Česka Zbrojovka A.S. v Praze”). Non-matching serial numbers: 67685 (frame and slide) and 18904 (barrel). No import marks. It was an improved version of the CZ 22, which had been licensed from Mauser. Production of the CZ 24 started in August 1925. The original order for 20,000 pistols was completed in June 1926. More orders followed, and by the end of 1929, 100,000 pistols had been accepted by the Military and Gendarmerie, called in Czechoslovakia the “Četnictvo”. Overall, approximately 200,000 CZ 24 pistols were made. An inventory on January 1, 1939, showed the Czechoslovak Army and Air Force had on hand 171,756 CZ 24 pistols. The regular serial number range for the CZ 24 pistol is: 12,000-190,000. The serial number of this pistol is 67,685. The pistol is factory dated 27 (1927) and it stayed in the factory warehouse until purchased by the Military in 1928. It displays the 1928 acceptance “J, rampant lion, 28” mark of Czechoslovak Military. CZ 24 is a meticulously crafted, well-built, robust, and reliable pistol that was very highly thought of at the time. During the German occupation (March 1939 – May 1945), the Czechoslovak Armed Forces were disarmed, and all the weapons were utilized by Germany and its allies. The CZ 24 pistols were not marked by the Germans, in any way, except for those used by the German Navy. CZ 24 pistols were also issued to the German Air Force, and Waffen-SS. The pistol is fitted with one-piece, smooth wood grips. Magazine capacity is eight rounds, and a Mauser Model 1910-style safety switch is mounted to the left of the pistol. Comes with a brown, durable, padded pistol case (rug) with zip closure.

title: For Sale:  MP5K-N MKE Z-5P MP5 Upgrades
postcontent:
Offered for sale is a MKE Z-5P clone of the MP5K.  Standard equipment includes the factory hard case, three steel 30 rd. mags, top sight rail, paddle mag release, push pin lower housing, cleaning kit, and user manual.  This model has the ½”x28 threaded muzzle and the three-lug for suppressor and accessory attachment. 
This weapon has been upgraded with a rare FBI designed AMBI semi auto trigger pack & US Navy Seal lower housing, Sig Brace tactical folding brace, 3 additional 30 rd mags, a dual mag coupler, front night sight.  Included in the offer is a rear sight adjustment tool, small pin sling hoop, single point sling, and soft carrying case.
The AMBI feature means that the selector switch is ambidextrous, allowing control in both right and left-handed shooting situations.  Standard lower and trigger packs are referred to as SEF and the selector is only on the left side.  The AMBI system takes more than a different selector, is requires a trigger box that will accept the ambidextrous selector.  AMBI was a requirement of the US Navy to purchase the MP5 & MP5K-N for use by the Navy SEALS.
The lower housing for this weapon is true US Navy SEAL.  The pictogram shows only safe, semi, and full auto.  The SEALS do not use burst fire weapons; the extra complexity of the trigger groups lower the weapon reliability.   Having this lower housing, does not trigger a NFA issue.  It is not capable of full auto fire. 
FAB Defense TZ-5 9mm/MP5 Magazine CouplerSig Brace Folding, SBTK-5Trijon Night Sight, frontHK Rear Sight Tool – Military ContractHas both the standard trigger pack and AMBI set 
This weapon has had approx. 500 fun and flawless rounds through it.  With the brace folded, this allows using the butt of the brace as a legal front grip.  With the brace extended, accuracy is through the roof.  I am in no hurry to see this go, just wondering if there is any serious shooters looking for the ultimate MP5K clone package.
